\[p(x)=\frac{e^{-3.09924-0.40489*x}}{1+e^{-3.09924-0.40489*x}}\]

ii

\[l(\beta_0,\beta)=\Pi_{i:y_i=1}(\hat{P}(default|student_i))\Pi_{i:y_i=0}(1-(\hat{P}(default|student_i))\]

iii

In Q1.1: 1 for student and 0 for non-student, the coefficient is what student is likely to default. In Q1.2: 0 for student and 1 for non-student, the coefficient is what non-student is likely to default. The coefficients of student in two model are the same value with opposite signals.

Compare the two models to see whether we should include Quote.

anova(olssale, olssale2, test='Chisq')
## Analysis of Deviance Table
## 
## Model 1: Status ~ Quote + Time.to.Delivery + Part.Type
## Model 2: Status ~ Time.to.Delivery + Part.Type
##   Resid. Df Resid. Dev Df Deviance Pr(>Chi)
## 1       546     723.83                     
## 2       547     724.22 -1 -0.39542   0.5295

According to the result, The chi-square value is not significant (0.53), indicating that the new model fits as well as the model with all variables. This confirms that the addition of the removed variable-Quote will not significantly improve the prediction accuracy of the equation. Thus we can use the simpler model.

LDA model

library(MASS)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
library(dplyr)
datawine3 <- datawine[,-c(14:16)]
datawine3$Quality <- as.factor(datawine3$Quality)
datawine3$Quality <- relevel(datawine3$Quality, ref='Just OK')
set.seed(0)
train = sample(nrow(datawine3), 0.8*nrow(datawine3))
datatrain <- datawine3[train,]
datatest <- datawine3[-train,]

train the model:

olswine1 <- lda(Quality~., datatrain)

Conclusion

Good quality wine seems to be:

  • high free.sulfur.dioxide, sulphates, alcohol;

  • low volatile.acidity, chlorides.

The results of LDA and multinomial logistic regression is different in fixed.acidity, residual.sugar and color.

To explore these differences, we need to take into account the interaction terms for further analysis.
